    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>TV Messages Work</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Phoenix House communications director Christopher Policano disputes Frank Rich's April 3 Op-Ed column criticizing anti-drug programming by ABC News (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re Frank Rich's criticism of ABC News's antidrug programming effort (column, April 3):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re Frank Rich's criticism of ABC News's antidrug programming effort (column, April 3):</p>
        <p>Before we throw out the baby with the bath water, a reminder: In the late l980's, when antidrug messages were a staple of prime-time television, adolescent drug use declined. In recent years, after the message was muted, many young people came to believe that drug use was less dangerous and more acceptable. Teen-age use doubled.</p>
        <p>CHRISTOPHER POLICANO  Director of Communications  Phoenix House  New York, April 7, 1997</p>
        <p>ABC Made Honest Effort to Talk About Drugs</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
